# Fluff Date: 2026-02-17 21:27:18
overview:<p>The Pack Hunter was the first new BattleMech design produced by Clan Wolf-in-Exile on Arc-Royal. Introduced in 3059 following the Refusal War, the thirty-ton light 'Mech was commissioned by Khan Phelan Kell as a pragmatic second-line design rather than the flagship OmniMech many warriors desired. Serving as a proof-of-concept for WC Site 3's nascent manufacturing capabilities, the Pack Hunter allowed the facility to identify and correct production issues before attempting more complex OmniMech designs.</p><p>Armed with a single extended-range PPC and built for speed and mobility, the Pack Hunter was designed to operate in pairs or small groups, harassing larger opponents through coordinated fire and superior maneuverability. Originally intended for obsolescence once OmniMech production began, repeated delays ensured the design remained in production until the introduction of the Pack Hunter II in 3077. The design was unexpectedly reborn decades later when the Wolf Empire repurposed a Technicron Manufacturing/Irian BattleMechs Unlimited plant on Tongatapu to produce an updated variant.</p>

capabilities:<p>Khan Phelan Kell's directive to create a 'Mech with impressive speed and a sharp bite resulted in a design built around a standard 210-rated Light Force fusion engine and seven Leaper Model L5 jump jets, granting the Pack Hunter a top speed exceeding one hundred nineteen kilometers per hour and a two-hundred-ten-meter jump capability. The use of a standard engine rather than an extralight model was a deliberate choice, reducing manufacturing costs while improving battlefield survivability through redundancy. Ten double heat sinks comfortably manage the thermal output of the sole weapon system.</p><p>That weapon, a Ripper Series A1 extended-range PPC mounted in the right torso, provides devastating firepower at extreme range, capable of threatening even heavy 'Mechs with well-placed shots. The Pack Hunter's tactical doctrine emphasizes coordinated engagements, with small groups working together to keep opponents at arm's length while concentrating fire. In field tests, as few as two Pack Hunters demonstrated a clear danger to even assault-class opponents such as the Dire Wolf, exploiting a novel interpretation of zellbrigen that allowed paired hunters to engage a single foe without dishonor.</p><p>The design's chief weakness is its reliance on a single weapon system, leaving it vulnerable when opponents close to short range. Four tons of Royal-7 standard armor on a Type AR1 endo steel chassis offer minimal protection against concentrated fire, making the Pack Hunter dependent on its speed and agility for survival.</p>

deployment:<p>The base Pack Hunter mounts a Ripper Series A1 extended-range PPC as its sole weapon on a thirty-ton endo steel frame powered by a standard 210-rated Light Force fusion engine. Seven Leaper Model L5 jump jets grant an impressive two-hundred-ten-meter jump range, while four tons of Royal-7 standard armor provide minimal but adequate protection for a design intended to engage at extreme range. The simplicity of the design was deliberate, Clan Wolf-in-Exile needed a reliable proof-of-concept for their Arc-Royal production lines, and the Pack Hunter delivered on that promise with its first deployment in 3059.</p>

history:<p>The Pack Hunter's history is inextricably tied to the fortunes of Clan Wolf-in-Exile. Following their harrowing escape from the Refusal War in 3057, the Exiled Wolves settled on Arc-Royal and immediately began constructing manufacturing infrastructure. WC Site 3 became their first functional production facility, and the Pack Hunter rolled off its lines in 3059 as the Clan's inaugural BattleMech design. The 'Mech's collaborative origins demonstrated the unique relationship between the Exiled Wolves and the Kell Hounds, standard armor and K9 communications equipment were purchased from Kell Hound manufacturers as part of a trade agreement for access to Clan endo steel produced in an Exiled Wolf orbital factory.</p><p>Though conceived as a stopgap, the Pack Hunter quickly proved its worth in combat. Garrison Stars attached to the First Wolf Strike Grenadiers deployed the design against Clan Smoke Jaguar forces on Albiero in 3059, where the 'Mech acquitted itself well despite limited numbers. The Exiled Wolves deployed Pack Hunters into second-line and garrison Clusters as quickly as they could be produced, supplemented by a handful delivered to the Kell Hounds for testing and training purposes.</p><p>Intended for replacement from the beginning, the Pack Hunter's production life was unexpectedly extended by repeated setbacks in developing its OmniMech successor. The Word of Blake's attack on Arc-Royal in March 3072 destroyed the original production line and forced a fundamental reassessment, ultimately resulting in the Pack Hunter II rather than the planned OmniMech. Several variants emerged from WC Site 3 before its destruction, the micro-laser-armed 2 in 3065, the MASC-equipped 3 in 3068, and the jump-capable 4 in 3070.</p><p>Remarkably, the Pack Hunter design resurfaced over seventy years later during the Dark Age. When the Wolf Empire seized the Technicron Manufacturing/Irian BattleMechs Unlimited plant on Tongatapu, they chose to repurpose the existing Hermes production line to build an updated Pack Hunter rather than converting it to produce Clan OmniMechs. The resulting Pack Hunter 5 blended Inner Sphere and Clan technologies into a faster, better-protected version of the original. The decision was a calculated political gesture intended to entice surviving Wolf-in-Exile warriors to join the Empire following the fall of Arc-Royal, though how the Empire acquired the original design plans remains a mystery.</p>

